definition.value: Convoluted duct structure posterior to the testis where one end (head of epidydimis) receives multiple efferent ductules from the testis and then drains to a single, larger caliber duct (body and tail of epidydimis) that continuous into the ductus deferens.
An organ zone of the uterine tube.
The ampulla is the second portion of the uterine tube. It is an intermediate dilated portion, which curves over the ovary. It is the most common site of human fertilization.
A small region of the uterine tube which connects the ampulla and infundibulum to the uterus.

The second part of the uterine tube located between the purple ampulla and the fimbriae. The infundibulum terminates with the ostium of uterine tube, surrounded by fimbriae, one of which (the "ovarian fimbria") is attached to the ovary. Together, the infundibulum and fimbria find the oocyte after ovulation.
A fringe of tissue around the ostium of the uterine tube, in the direction of the ovary.
The region of the uterine tube which is located in the fundus of the uterus and is continuous with the isthmus.
A serous membrane that is part of a fallopian tube.
The subserosa of the uterine tube.
A layer of smooth muscle in the uterine tube.
A mucosa that is part of the uterine tube.
One of the fimbria of the uterine tube which is long enough to reach the ovary.
A fold of musoca which is part of the uterine tube.
The internal and external surfaces of the ovary.
The pole of the ovary which faces the uterine tube.
The pole of the ovary which faces the uterus.

The layer of the ovarian stroma lying immediately beneath the tunica albuginea, composed of connective tissue cells and fibers, among which are scattered primary and secondary (antral) follicles in various stages of development; the cortex varies in thickness according to the age of the individual, becoming thinner with advancing years; included in the follicles are the cumulus oophorus, membrana granulosa (and the granulosa cells inside it), corona radiata, zona pellucida, and primary oocyte; the zona pellucida, theca of follicle, antrum and liquor folliculi are also contained in the follicle; also in the cortex is the corpus luteum derived from the follicles.
The outer layer of the ovary, composed of cellular connective tissue which contains the ovarian follicles.

Highly vascular stroma found in the center of the ovary that forms from embryonic mesenchyme and contains blood vessels, lymphatic vessels, and nerves; this stroma forms the tissue of the hilum by which the ovarian ligament is attached, and through which the blood vessels enter; it does not contain any ovarian follicles.
The central portion of the ovary, composed of loose connective tissue that contains blood vessels, lymph vessels and nerves.

A group of cells that remain of the Graafian follicle following ovulation. This structure is composed of endocrine tissue and produces progesterone. This is needed to prepare the uterine lining for implantation by the fertilized egg.
The yellow body derived from the ruptured ovarian follicle after ovulation. The process of corpus luteum formation, luteinization, is regulated by luteinizing hormone.
White fibrous tissue that replaces the regressing corpus luteum in the human ovary in the latter half of pregnancy, or soon after ovulation when pregnancy does not supervene.

The stroma of the ovary is a peculiar soft tissue, abundantly supplied with blood vessels, consisting for the most part of spindle-shaped cells with a small amount of ordinary connective tissue. These cells have been regarded by some anatomists as unstriped muscle cells, which, indeed, they most resemble; by others as connective-tissue cells. On the surface of the organ this tissue is much condensed, and forms a layer composed of short connective-tissue fibers, with fusiform cells between them. The stroma of the ovary may contain interstitial cells resembling those of the testis.
A depression in the ovary where the ovarian ligament attaches and blood vessels and nerves enter or leave the ovary.
The excretory duct of the testes that carries spermatozoa. It rises from the scrotum and joins the seminal vesicles to form the ejaculatory duct.
One of the columns of erectile tissue forming the dorsum and sides of the penis.
The circumference of the base of the glans forms a rounded projecting border, the corona of the glans penis, overhanging a deep retroglandular sulcus, behind which is the neck of the penis.
A retractable double-layered fold of skin and mucous membrane that covers the glans penis and protects the urinary meatus when the penis is not erect.
Secretion produced by preputial gland.
Organ with organ cavity, each intance of which connects some cavity of the urinary bladder to the exterior.

Urethra, each instance of which is a canal extending from the neck of some urinary bladder to some urinary meatus, and divided into some four parts: from some urinary bladder, pars intramuralis (or pars preprostatica), pars prostatica, pars membranacea (or pars intermedia), and the pars spongiosa.
The 1.5 inch long tube carrying urine from the bladder to the outside of the body exiting between the clitoris and vagina.

Mesentery, each instance of which is a peritoneal fold lateral to and above some ovary which extends out to the wall of some pelvis; it contains some ovarian vessels and nerves and passes upward over some iliac vessels.
Breast which has as its parts fibroglandular mass, most common in individuals who have undergone some form of feminization.
Breast which has as its parts simple lactiferous duct, most common in individuals who have undergone some form of virilization.
Organ segment which is regional part of vagina.

The space posterior to the glans clitoridis, between the labia minora; located within the vestibule are the openings of the vagina, the urethra, and the ducts of the lesser vestibular glands, the greater vestibular (Bartholin's) glands, and the paraurethral (Skene's) glands, which release mucus into the vestibule to maintain a moist, lubricated vestibular environment; the vestibule is also moistened by secretions from the cervical mucus glands located in the inferior region of the uterus.
The anterior wall of the vagina.
The posterior wall of the vagina.
A mucosa that is part of the vagina.
The mucosal layer of the vagina.
Any one of the four small recessed areas (anterior, posterior, and two lateral) that are formed between the margin of the cervix and the vaginal wall.
The vaginal fornix that is front of the cervix. It is close to the vesico-uterine pouch.
The vaginal fornix that is behind the cervix. It is close to the recto-uterine pouch.
The vaginal fornix that is to the side of the cervix.
The opening between the labia majora.
Longitudinal ridges on the inner surface of the mucous membrane of the vagina.

definition.value: Longitudinal ridges on the anterior inner surface of the mucous membrane of the vagina.

label.value: column of posterior wall of vagina

definition.value: Longitudinal ridges on the posterior inner surface of the mucous membrane of the vagina.
A retractable double-layered fold of skin and mucous membrane that covers the clitoral glans.
One of a pair of sponge-like regions of erectile tissue which contain most of the blood in the clitoris during clitoral erection.

Anatomical cavity that connects an organ cavity, organ cavity subdivision or cavity of body part subdivision to the exterior, completely or partially surrounded by organs or organ parts that are lined by epithelium.
A rounded prominence of adipose tissue overlying the pubic symphysis and adjacent pubic bone.
